I think some of your peers noted a strong start to the year and perhaps a slowdown exiting the Q. I'm just curious on what kind of trends you saw to our 4Q.

Geoff Martha -- Chairman and Chief Executive Officer

Sure, Vijay. Thanks for the question. Good to talk to you. Well, yeah, for -- you know, procedure volume was a tailwind for us, you know, relative to prior quarters.

I mean, Europe, in particular, recovered well and was out and front. U.S. lagged a little bit, but it began to accelerate in April and May. So, like I said, Western Europe, high-single-digit growth and, you know, staffing issues improving.

And, you know, beyond that, better product availability resulted in a strong back half of the Q4 for us in Western Europe. But clearly, staffing issue is getting better. Emerging markets, you know, grew 11%, mid-teens if you exclude China. And then Japan was mid-single digits.

So, we're seeing around the world a strong pickup. Like I said, U.S. lagged, you know, but we saw a strong April and into May pickup there. So, that -- you know, that's how I'd characterize the procedures.

If you kind of look at it, you know, beyond geography, if you look at it maybe by therapy or product area for us, you know, surgical and GI procedures and med surge, as well as TAVR procedures and some more elective procedures like pain stim, you know, picked up, I think, due to improved staffing. You know, CRM was notable, with good initial implant growth and, you know, for Medtronic specifically, coming out of a replacement headwind. You know, maybe one outlier might be coronary, still behind, and procedure volume recovery. But that's how I look at it by geography and by therapy area.

